english:
  title: Record of the Hall of Nurturing Clumsiness
  author: Shin Gae
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Since my youth, my nature has been open and unrestrained. I have always despised the cunning tricks of the marketplace and court intrigue. So I sought out a quiet, secluded corner south of the city walls and built the Hall of Nurturing Clumsiness. In all my daily comings and goings, I keep company only with Clumsiness, never parting from it for even a moment. On still nights beneath the bright moon, when all creatures rest, I recline upon a high pillow and listen to the wind whisper through the pines.

    Some worldly people have criticized me for cultivating Clumsiness for so long. Doubting myself, I once tried to send it away. But Clumsiness clung to me, unwilling to depart, and seemed almost displeased by my rejection. Then I came to my senses and reflected: "I have cherished Clumsiness for many years now. I fear that Cunning, wounded by my neglect, may refuse to return. Should both abandon me, I would be left desolate as a stray dog without a home. Better to keep Clumsiness close as before and honor our ancient pact."

    Though Clumsiness has no visible form or sound, its spiritual wisdom far surpasses that of any human. When I am tempted by profit, it admonishes me with the examples of Robber Zhi and Bo Yi. When I seek fame, it rebukes me with the deeds of Fan Li and Wen Zhong. When I am moved toward deception, it shows me how great villains met ruin while the truly foolish lived out their natural spans. Beyond this, whenever I stray from righteousness or abandon the Way, it gently guides me back. My high rank and long life owe much to Clumsiness's faithful protection.

    Hearing the world's gossip gnawed at me, yet I reproached myself: "I am indeed a base person, ungrateful and forgetful of duty—the greatest misfortune. I shall keep Clumsiness in this hall as before." So I made my sincere apologies and resolved to dwell here with Clumsiness to the end of my days.

    Moreover, I wish to pass this hall to all generations, so that my descendants never abandon this principle. Should anyone disobey my words, they will be unfilial and disloyal, and I shall lodge complaint with Heaven itself. Now that my friend has taken up this same aim of nurturing Clumsiness, I see in it the highest virtue. Moved by your noble resolve, I find our hearts beat as one. From this day forward, let us walk together in this Way, that we may never forsake such sacred purpose.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Robber Zhi (盜跖) and Bo Yi (伯夷) represent opposing extremes: one a notorious bandit, the other an ascetic sage who starved rather than serve an unjust ruler. Together they illustrate the perils of both ambition and moral rigidity.'
  - key: ''
    value: Fan Li (范蠡) and Wen Zhong (文種) were advisors to the Kingdom of Yue. While Fan Li withdrew with honor and died naturally, Wen Zhong was persecuted despite his loyalty—a lesson on the dangers of seeking fame and position.
